english:
  title: Record of the Sunflower Pavilion
  author: Lee Seok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Kwon Hui-an of Yongga is one whom I love and revere. Clear without forced singularity, harmonious without forced conformity, he has stood long in the court yet found no occasion to fulfill his aspirations. Taking the image of the sunflower turning toward the sun, he inscribed his pavilion "Sunflower" and asked me to write this record. I could not refuse, and so I set down what I have learned:

    The Way is formless, yet dwells in all things. In their forms, it finds expression. Thus the Dragon Chart and Turtle Book are the models of sages, and the yarrow's growth, revealing the mysteries of yin and yang, became the foundation for opening things and accomplishing tasks for ten thousand generations. Can we say any living thing is insignificant? The modern study of plum blossoms likewise traces to this principle—extend it to all things and it naturally unfolds. Who could abandon it?

    Thus Hui-an's great-grandfather, Minister Munjong, whose virtue and letters guided a hundred officials, named his dwelling "Chrysanthemum Study." His grandfather, Lord Changhwa, crowned in merit and fortune above all others, named his dwelling "Pine Study." And his father, bearing the seal of ten thousand households and commanding the power of the imperial consort's house, built a pavilion beside the lotus pond in Sungyo village, naming it "Cloud Brocade." There he brought joy to his kin and extended it to all the clan—the great Minister Munjong himself wrote its record. How splendid!

    Now when Hui-an chooses the sunflower, it is the family way. The sunflower appears in the Spring and Autumn Annals, and the Master of Shusui took it up and wrote it into poetry. Great indeed is the sunflower's fortune. The flowers of water and earth are countless, yet only the sunflower knows to guard its roots—this is wisdom. Only the sunflower turns toward the sun—this is loyalty. How could the gentleman's regard for it be mere chance?

    When frost falls, the chrysanthemum yellows. When snow deepens, the pine stays green. When wind and rain scatter, the lotus fragrance grows ever clearer. When the sun shines bright, the sunflower's heart must turn. Far does it differ from ordinary plants. Who would not love and revere it?

    The chrysanthemum represents reclusion, the pine represents integrity, the lotus represents the gentleman, and the sunflower represents wisdom and loyalty. How remarkable that all four gather in a single house! Grandfather, father, and son, generation following generation, each taking these as their self-expression. Clearly, the Kwon family shall not decay like common weeds. They will shine upon the scholarly world and spread renown throughout the realm—of this we may be certain. Let this be recorded.

    Written in the twelfth month of the year Jeongsa.
  footnotes:
    - The Dragon Chart and Turtle Book (龍圖龜書) are legendary diagrams said to have appeared on the back of a dragon and turtle respectively, revealing cosmic principles to the ancients.
    - The yarrow (蓍草) was used in ancient divination and represents the embodiment of natural principles.
    - The Master of Shusui (涑水先生) refers to Sima Guang, the renowned Song dynasty scholar.
    - 'The Kwon family''s naming of their dwellings after plants—chrysanthemum, pine, lotus, and sunflower—each represents different virtues: hermitic withdrawal, steadfast integrity, noble character, and devoted loyalty respectively.'
